# Code Style & Quality Guidelines

## Code Structure & Organization

Keep code clean and self-documenting through proper structure:

- Extract business logic into well-named functions
- Keep main/orchestration functions clean and focused on data flow
- Each function should have a single responsibility
- Use descriptive, verb-based function names: `fetch`, `find`, `save`, `process`, `emit`
- Avoid inline comments - prefer self-documenting code through proper naming

```ts#good-example.ts
// Good: Clean orchestration function with extracted business logic
async function processSubreddit(subreddit: string, ...deps): Promise<void> {
  return tracer.with(`Process /r/${subreddit}`, async (ctx) => {
    const posts = await fetchThreadsFromReddit(subreddit, redditClient, tracer);
    if (posts.length === 0) {
      ctx.log.info({ subreddit }, 'No threads found');
      return;
    }

    const newPosts = await findNewThreads(posts, db, tracer);
    if (newPosts.length === 0) {
      return;
    }

    await processNewThreads(newPosts, db, producer, tracer);
  });
}
```

## Function Extraction Guidelines

Extract operations that:

- Perform a distinct business operation
- Would benefit from separate tracing/logging
- Can be tested independently
- Improve readability of the main function

```ts#extraction-example.ts
// Extract: fetching data from external source
async function fetchThreadsFromReddit(
  subreddit: string,
  redditClient: RedditClient,
  tracer: Tracer,
): Promise<RedditPost[]> {
  return tracer.with(`Fetch threads from /r/${subreddit}`, async (ctx) => {
    const posts = await redditClient.fetchSubredditPosts(subreddit);
    ctx.log.info({ subreddit, count: posts.length }, `Fetched ${posts.length} threads`);
    return posts;
  });
}

// Extract: database lookup/filtering
async function findNewThreads(
  posts: RedditPost[],
  db: DBClient,
  tracer: Tracer,
): Promise<RedditPost[]> {
  return tracer.with('Find new threads', async (ctx) => {
    // ... implementation
  });
}

// Extract: persistence operation
async function saveThreadToDB(
  post: RedditPost,
  db: DBClient,
  tracer: Tracer,
): Promise<RedditThread> {
  return tracer.with(`Save thread ${post.id}`, async (ctx) => {
    // ... implementation
  });
}
```

## Logging Practices

Always use `ctx.log` from the tracing context. Use structured logging with context object first, message second.
Use log level `info` before an operation with relevant context, and `debug` level after an operation with crucial response values and relevant context.

### Log Levels

- `debug`: Detailed information for debugging (state, intermediate values)
- `info`: Important business events (fetched X items, processing started/completed)
- `error`: Errors with full context

```ts#logging-example.ts
// Good: Structured logging with context
ctx.log.info({ subreddit, count: posts.length }, `Fetched ${posts.length} threads`);
ctx.log.debug({ threadId: insertedThread.id, redditId: post.id }, 'Thread saved to database');
ctx.log.error({ error, subreddit }, `Failed to fetch threads from /r/${subreddit}`);

// Bad: Unstructured logging
ctx.log.info(`Fetched ${posts.length} threads from ${subreddit}`);
ctx.log.error('Something went wrong');
```

### Logging Guidelines

- Include relevant context in log objects (IDs, counts, relevant state)
- Log at function entry/exit for important operations
- Use descriptive, action-oriented log messages
- Don't log sensitive data

## Tracing Practices

All business logic functions must use `tracer.with()` or `ctx.with()` for observability.

```ts#tracing-example.ts
// Top-level function uses tracer.with()
async function fetchThreadsFromReddit(subreddit: string, tracer: Tracer) {
  return tracer.with(`Fetch threads from /r/${subreddit}`, async (ctx) => {
    // ... implementation
  });
}

// Nested operations use ctx.with()
async function detect(signal: SignalMetric, ctx: Context): Promise<void> {
  await ctx.with('Price spike detection', async (c) => {
    c.annotate('signal.id', signal.id);
    c.annotate('signal.type', signal.type);
    // ... implementation
  });
}
```

### Tracing Guidelines

- Use descriptive span names that explain what the operation does
- Use `ctx.annotate()` to add important metadata to spans
- Use `ctx.setName()` to update span names dynamically when context is known
- Span names should be clear and concise

## Error Handling

Wrap orchestration functions in try-catch blocks. Log errors with full context before throwing.

```ts#error-handling-example.ts
async function processSubreddit(subreddit: string, ...deps): Promise<void> {
  return tracer.with(`Process /r/${subreddit}`, async (ctx) => {
    try {
      const posts = await fetchThreadsFromReddit(subreddit, redditClient, tracer);
      // ... rest of processing
    } catch (error) {
      ctx.log.error({ error, subreddit }, `Failed to process /r/${subreddit}`);
      throw error;
    }
  });
}
```

## TypeScript Patterns

```ts#typescript-patterns.ts
// Use type imports for type-only imports
import type { DBClient, RedditThread } from '@modules/db';
import { makeRedditThread, schema } from '@modules/db';

// Prefer explicit return types for extracted functions
async function findNewThreads(
  posts: RedditPost[],
  db: DBClient,
  tracer: Tracer,
): Promise<RedditPost[]> {
  // ...
}

// Use assertion functions for runtime validation
function ensureExists<T>(
  value: T | undefined | null,
  ctx: Context,
  message?: string,
): asserts value is T {
  if (value === undefined || value === null) {
    const errorMessage = message || 'Expected value to exist';
    ctx.log.error(errorMessage);
    throw new Error(errorMessage);
  }
}
```

## Service Factory Pattern

Use the `makeXService` pattern for creating services with dependencies:

```ts#service-factory.ts
export interface MakeThreadFetcherServiceOpts {
  db: DBClient;
  tracer: Tracer;
  producer: Producer;
}

export function makeThreadFetcherService(opts: MakeThreadFetcherServiceOpts) {
  const { db, tracer, producer } = opts;
  const redditClient = makeRedditClient();

  return {
    async fetchThreads() {
      for (const subreddit of SUBREDDITS) {
        await processSubreddit(subreddit, redditClient, db, producer, tracer);
      }
    },
  };
}
```

## Code Comments

Avoid comments that explain "what" - code should be self-documenting. Only use comments for:

- Complex algorithms that need explanation
- "Why" explanations for non-obvious decisions
- JSDoc for exported functions/interfaces when needed

```ts#comments-example.ts
// Bad: Comment explains what the code does
// Check if posts array is empty and return early
if (posts.length === 0) {
  return;
}

// Good: Self-documenting code, no comment needed
const newPosts = await findNewThreads(posts, db, tracer);
if (newPosts.length === 0) {
  return;
}

// Good: Comment explains WHY (non-obvious decision)
// Using ZLEMA instead of SMA for faster response to price changes
const lag = 2 / (1 + alpha);
```

